.SH EXCLUDING FILES
.PP
In reverse mode, it is possible to exclude files from the encrypted
view, using the \f[V]-exclude\f[R], \f[V]-exclude-wildcard\f[R] and
\f[V]-exclude-from\f[R] options.
.PP
\f[V]-exclude\f[R] matches complete paths, so
\f[V]-exclude file.txt\f[R] only excludes a file named
\f[V]file.txt\f[R] in the root of the mounted filesystem; files named
\f[V]file.txt\f[R] in subdirectories are still visible.
Wildcards are NOT supported.
This option is kept for compatibility with the behavior up to version
1.6.x.
New users should use \f[V]-exclude-wildcard\f[R] instead.
.PP
\f[V]-exclude-wildcard\f[R] uses gitignore syntax and matches files
anywhere, so \f[V]-exclude-wildcard file.txt\f[R] excludes files named
\f[V]file.txt\f[R] in any directory.
If you want to match complete paths, you can prefix the filename with a
\f[V]/\f[R]: \f[V]-exclude-wildcard /file.txt\f[R] excludes only
\f[V]file.txt\f[R] in the root of the mounted filesystem.
.PP
If there are many exclusions, you can use \f[V]-exclude-from\f[R] to
read gitignore patterns from a file.
As with \f[V]-exclude-wildcard\f[R], use a leading \f[V]/\f[R] to match
complete paths.
.PP
The rules for exclusion are that of
gitignore (https://git-scm.com/docs/gitignore#_pattern_format).
In short:
.IP "1." 3
A blank line matches no files, so it can serve as a separator for
readability.
.IP "2." 3
A line starting with \f[V]#\f[R] serves as a comment.
Put a backslash (\f[V]\[rs]\f[R]) in front of the first hash for
patterns that begin with a hash.
.IP "3." 3
Trailing spaces are ignored unless they are quoted with backslash
(\f[V]\[rs]\f[R]).
.IP "4." 3
An optional prefix \f[V]!\f[R] negates the pattern; any matching file
excluded by a previous pattern will become included again.
It is not possible to re-include a file if a parent directory of that
file is excluded.
Put a backslash (\f[V]\[rs]\f[R]) in front of the first \f[V]!\f[R] for
patterns that begin with a literal \f[V]!\f[R], for example,
\f[V]\[rs]!important!.txt\f[R].
.IP "5." 3
If the pattern ends with a slash, it is removed for the purpose of the
following description, but it would only find a match with a directory.
In other words, \f[V]foo/\f[R] will match a directory foo and paths
underneath it, but will not match a regular file or a symbolic link foo.
.IP "6." 3
If the pattern does not contain a slash \f[V]/\f[R], it is treated as a
shell glob pattern and checked for a match against the pathname relative
to the root of the mounted filesystem.
.IP "7." 3
Otherwise, the pattern is treated as a shell glob suitable for
consumption by fnmatch(3) with the FNM_PATHNAME flag: wildcards in the
pattern will not match a \f[V]/\f[R] in the pathname.
For example, \f[V]Documentation/*.html\f[R] matches
\f[V]Documentation/git.html\f[R] but not
\f[V]Documentation/ppc/ppc.html\f[R] or
\f[V]tools/perf/Documentation/perf.html\f[R].
.IP "8." 3
A leading slash matches the beginning of the pathname.
For example, \f[V]/*.c\f[R] matches \f[V]cat-file.c\f[R] but not
\f[V]mozilla-sha1/sha1.c\f[R].
.IP "9." 3
Two consecutive asterisks (\f[V]**\f[R]) in patterns matched against
full pathname may have special meaning:
.RS 4
.IP "  i." 5
A leading \f[V]**\f[R] followed by a slash means match in all
directories.
For example, \f[V]**/foo\f[R] matches file or directory \f[V]foo\f[R]
anywhere, the same as pattern \f[V]foo\f[R].
\f[V]**/foo/bar\f[R] matches file or directory \f[V]bar\f[R] anywhere
that is directly under directory \f[V]foo\f[R].
.IP " ii." 5
A trailing \f[V]/**\f[R] matches everything inside.
For example, \f[V]abc/**\f[R] matches all files inside directory
\f[V]abc\f[R], with infinite depth.
.IP "iii." 5
A slash followed by two consecutive asterisks then a slash matches zero
or more directories.
For example, \f[V]a/**/b\f[R] matches \f[V]a/b\f[R], \f[V]a/x/b\f[R],
\f[V]a/x/y/b\f[R] and so on.
.IP " iv." 5
Other consecutive asterisks are considered invalid.
.RE
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Init
.PP
Create an encrypted filesystem in directory \[lq]mydir.crypt\[rq], mount
it on \[lq]mydir\[rq]:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
mkdir mydir.crypt mydir
gocryptfs -init mydir.crypt
gocryptfs mydir.crypt mydir
\f[R]
.fi
.SS Mount
.PP
Mount an encrypted view of joe\[cq]s home directory using reverse mode:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
mkdir /home/joe.crypt
gocryptfs -init -reverse /home/joe
gocryptfs -reverse /home/joe /home/joe.crypt
\f[R]
.fi
.SS fstab
.PP
Adding this line to \f[V]/etc/fstab\f[R] will mount
\f[V]/tmp/cipher\f[R] to \f[V]/tmp/plain\f[R] on boot, using the
password in \f[V]/tmp/passfile\f[R].
Use \f[V]sudo mount -av\f[R] to test the line without having to reboot.
Adjust the gocryptfs path acc.
to the output of the command \f[V]which gocryptfs\f[R].
Do use the \f[V]nofail\f[R] option to prevent an unbootable system if
the gocryptfs mount fails (see the \f[V]-nofail\f[R] option for
details).
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
/tmp/cipher /tmp/plain fuse./usr/local/bin/gocryptfs nofail,allow_other,passfile=/tmp/password 0 0
\f[R]
.fi
